[2] UK (Scotland)
Date: Thu 10 Oct 2013
Source: The Scotsman [edited]
http://www.scotsman.com/news/health/no-new-rise-in-scottish-measles-cases-1-3133929


An increase in measles cases earlier this year [2013] has not continued in the last 3 months, figures show. There were 151 clinically suspected measles cases in the 1st 9 months of 2013, up from 57 cases over the same period last year [2012], a Health Protection Scotland (HPS) report has found. Cases of the infection had risen sharply earlier this year with 100 notifications of suspected measles between April and June 2013, but there were only 30 since then and September 2013.

There have been 51 laboratory confirmed cases of measles so far in 2013, but only 3 in the last 3 months, the figures show. The HPS figures identified 3 clusters of cases, including one which occurred in a school, between April and June 2013 that contributed to the increase. HPS said the majority of cases were in unvaccinated or under-immunised individuals, those who have not received the recommended 2 doses of the MMR vaccine. The HPS report said: "The large increase in the number of cases seen in Scotland in weeks 9-24 has not continued into the current quarter. Clusters of cases and a high number of sporadic cases of unknown exposure origin are no longer being seen. Of the 51 cases so far in 2013, cases had a median age of 15 years. The majority of cases were unvaccinated or under-immunised (those who have not received the recommended 2 doses of MMR vaccine)."

Last year [2012], Public Health England reported the highest annual number of measles cases for the last 18 years with more than 2000 cases.

Chief Medical Officer Sir Harry Burns announced in May 2013 that older children would be offered a vaccination against measles following the outbreaks south of the border. Health boards in Scotland wrote to parents of unvaccinated children or those who are only partially protected to offer them the MMR vaccine or a booster shot.

Other figures released in the HPS report show that the number of confirmed cases of mumps so far this year [2013] has fallen to 211 compared to 405 for the same period last year [2012]. The report said mumps cases continue to occur steadily in Scotland among young adults who have not received 2 doses of MMR vaccine.

